The Italian Presidency of the European Union bears a huge responsibility to reinvigorate the enlargement as an essential aspect of the new EU.
The best place to start would be to encourage a better attitude towards adoption of the euro for the countries acceding to the Union.
In fact, the paternalistic position of the institutions of the EU to the accession countries threatens to create a two-speed Europe that will complicate the process of integration.
The accession countries have kept their market share in realizing trade integration with the EU countries sometimes further than in many Member countries.
Three of them - the Estonia, the Latvia and Lithuania - have a currency board system or fixed exchange rate with the euro, just like Bulgaria, who must join the Union in 2007.
Others showed several years their interest to adopt the euro from the start, in a unilateral way in some cases, even before they arrive in the Union - a position openly advocated by the National Bank of Poland, and to a lesser extent by the National Bank of Hungary and the National Bank of the Czech Republic.
Yet, despite their progress to bring their inflation rates and interest rates closer to European levels, many candidate countries fear, with full opening on the movement of capital, prerequisites for accession to the Union, exposing themselves to the risk of judgments brutal movements of capital and crisis currency.
They understood the lessons from Latin America and Asia in the 1990s.
The adoption of the euro would allow them easily to escape such risks and concentrate their efforts on the creation of a real growth for their economies.
However, the response of the European institutions and particularly the European Central Bank and the European Commission was negative: candidate countries agreed retort that they must first spend two years in the European exchange rate mechanism (ERM II), where euro aspirants had to prove what were able to their policies.
Initially, even the currency board systems were considered unacceptable, although, as is often the case in Europe, exceptions have been made: countries with currency board systems could keep them even after their accession to the Union.
The opposition of the ECB and the Commission to an early adoption of the euro is ill-founded.
What should count for the European Union remains that any Member State policies are not harmful to the other Member States.
As noted by Leszek Balcerowicz, the Governor of the National Bank of Poland, the adoption of the euro by candidate countries creates certainly benefits for the candidate countries while, in the worst cases, entirely without effect for existing members.
Indeed, the economic combined weight of all the candidate countries is far too low - only 6% of the GDP of the EU expanded - to exercise an effect on the euro.
However, the continuing opposition of the EU institutions has pushed most of the candidate countries to abandon the idea of adopting the euro unilaterally or as soon as possible after their entry into the Union.
Unfortunately, the stubbornness of the ECB and the Commission now bring water to the mill of populist governments in the accession countries who rely on the variation of the rate of Exchange to escape the fiscal discipline that involves the adoption of the euro.
However, such tax manoeuvres would probably disqualify a country wishing to quickly enter the eurozone.
In fact, the accession countries which have not set up a currency board system have seen their budget deficits ignite - exceeding 9% of GDP in Hungary in 2002 and more than 5% in Poland, Czech Republic and Slovakia - while major capital movements have exerted strong pressure on their currencies so they rise.
This trend exposes the real economies of the candidate countries at risk of reversal of the flow of capital and crisis currency that early adoption of the euro would eliminate.
Ironically, the candidate countries are lecturing by the officials of the ECB and the Commission on the trade-off between nominal convergence and real convergence.
It appears that the only requirement of Brussels or the objective of growth of the candidate countries, macroeconomic stability can wait.
Large budget deficits support growth, and inflation is clearly not a problem.
