This was, of course, the adoption of economic policies on the market forces in the former Communist countries which led to the gates of EU membership.
Thus, the institutions European should drop their paternalistic approach and take seriously the concerns of the central banks of the candidate countries about the risks associated with maintaining their own currency over a long period during which their economies must open up completely to capital movements.
Today, the ECB and the European Commission supported de facto the positions of populist governments of Eastern Europe that already spend funds that they hope to obtain in the future on the part of the EU.
It is high time that the European institutions address more responsibly to the challenges and opportunities posed by enlargement.
They could start by considering early adoption of the euro by the applicant countries of a more favourable eye, both for the countries with a currency board system for those using a floating exchange rate.
