The interventionist syndrome.
Kosovo often plays the role of conflict - test for the "humanitarian" intervention concept.
But while the Iraq enters the spiral of chaos, diplomats and leaders of all nationalities are wondering again whether it is appropriate for alliances of nations or the international community to intervene when a sovereign country appears unable or unwilling to defend its citizens against genocide, war crimes or ethnic cleansing.
At the centre of this debate is the so-called doctrine of the "responsibility to protection".
As a mediator in Kosovo appointed by Nations - United these past five years, I had the unique opportunity to observe the effects of this doctrine after the intervention of NATO in the former Yugoslavia in 1999.
Kosovo has become an international experience of construction of society, led by the administrative Mission ad interim of the United Nations in Kosovo (UNMIK).
Experience is the right word here.
Indeed, Kosovo has turned into the international response test tube.
I've lived and worked long enough in Kosovo to see the result, and I contend that such experiments require further research.
It is clear that the need for international intervention in a crisis depends on each specific period, and a rapid reaction is often necessary.
However, military factors set aside, there where such interventions are considered it is vital to focus the discussions of international policy on the deployment of a civilian presence and security related one to the other.
It is even more true when human suffering is caused by community conflicts, as was the case in Kosovo.
The immediate deployment of a civilian presence and adequate security directly after the end of the 1999 NATO bombing could provide appropriate mechanisms to protect against the return of stick that allowed victims to become torturers.
NATO peacekeeping forces had no mission is to prevent the abductions, disappearances, murderous revenge and the destruction of properties by Albanian ethnic groups, which has led to a vast ethnic cleansing reversed of the non - Albanian population (mostly Serbian).
Consequence of this neglect, a social and political residue deleterious permeates the current Kosovo.
Rather than appease community conflicts, inter-ethnic hatred is more virulent than ever.
In addition to the lack of a civilian presence and security to reassure every community, the lack in general of judicial mechanism to render rapid justice for crimes committed during and after the intervention has created additional tension.
This tension is so pervasive, in fact, that any perspective to start if necessary process of reconciliation must now be pushed back to a distant future.
Similarly, in Kosovo the international community spent that little time to help veterans to consider their collective responsibility for the atrocities, as their personal involvement was direct or indirect.
Without such an effort, try to improve the situation is to build a House on a pile of sand.
This lack of foresight and projects concerning the aftermath of armed intervention is not only dangerous for the officially "rescued" people, it's also counter - productive.
When a humanitarian intervention is not structured to ensure basic security, - underlying antagonisms that inspired the intervention at the base is only strengthened, and not diminished.
Six years after the intervention of NATO, Kosovo seems further away than ever the stability and social peace.
Despite assurances renewed of the authorities of the United Nations that Kosovo is on the path of reconciliation and genuine autonomy, NATO representatives indicate that there are projects of maintaining a long-term military presence in the province to "ensure that the political process will be implemented successfully".
This brings me to another key point: a possible exit strategy is as important to the success of any future humanitarian intervention as the input policy.
For international intervention has a real chance to succeed, it should from the outset to define the criteria for "success".
Only such clarity can allow to correctly an end to the commitment of international actors.
In Kosovo, such clarity is and has been lacking; Therefore, NATO and the UN have no clear idea about when or how they should both withdraw.
One day, someone said accurately that it is easy to bomb, but much more difficult to rebuild; It is relatively easy to defeat a regime militarily, but it is much harder to build a strong and sustainable civil society in its place.
The General Assembly of the United Nations should keep this idea in memory when it will begin to codify the doctrine of the "responsibility to protection".
