Being in deficit, a country increases its national debt and imposes a burden on future generations.
Politicians naturally prefer to conceal the manner in which to perform the movements of resources between generations.
They are designed primarily to address immediate problems and to reap the promised benefits today.
Accountants who compute government deficits trying to stop politicians to fool us by making us accept the benefits that they offer without understanding what will the future cost.
But these accountants offer us no method for determining when deficits are justifiable and when they are not.
Deficits result not only immediate political problems, but also problems of distributive intergenerational justice and inter generations risk-sharing.
No generation should be required to accept unnecessary economic risks imposed by another generation.
The possibility that deficits must correctly process future generations depends on the manner in which are designed a government expenditure and taxation systems.
Proponents of an uninterrupted deficit often depict him as an evil necessary to restore an economy where confidence crumbles.
Inspired by Keynes, they argue that uninterrupted deficits will restore confidence before occurrence of a recession or a depression.
But this is actually equivalent to administer Prozac to a patient before he becomes suicidal.
Such arguments, although they are quite legitimate at times, have limits.
The public deficits of the Japan resulted in a national debt amounting to 140% of annual GDP without to make an economic resurgence.
Indeed, the current budget deficits reflect long-term problems that are not at all what Keynesian theory predicts.
Discussions on deficits must be redefined in terms of problems inter generations important over the long term.
The problems are subtle, because they depend on the actions of future Governments.
In the past, some Governments, when they were faced with huge national debts, "deflating them" effectively.
They thus removing the burden on the next generation which is actually returned to investors who are not retired from the first bond market signs of rising prices or which have delayed acquisition of their house so that inflation would have wiped out the real value of their mortgages.
Governments could again decide to act in this sense, everything especially if national debts believe more.
