Some politicians can again succeed in anchoring the idea that inflation, while challenging, is a boon for the economy.
But also officially measured current government deficits, must also reckon with some imminent obligations caused by a demographic change (declining birth rate) and with the prospect of payments of sums for social benefits in the future.
The scope of these obligations is monumental.
In their 2003 report, the Trustees of the US Social Security Administration Trust Funds estimate that maintaining the solvency of the system of social security for the next 75 years will cost $ 3.5 trillion, or about the amount of the current total debt of the U.S. Government ($3.9 trillion).
The Trustees of the US Medicare Trust Funds (which brings medical services retirees) estimate that floating obligations are now worth $ 5.9 trillion, or more than half of the official national debt of America.
The possibility of a budget shortfall for social security and health is worse in Europe and Japan because of more difficult demographic statistics.
Moreover, in contrast to the official national debt, social benefits obligations are not related to the currency.
They are rather the promise of a certain standard of living (including the value of medical services), corrected for inflation.
No Government can therefore "deflate".
But this does not mean insofar as pensions and other social obligations are completely frozen.
This means that the problem is political.
Pensioners are one of the most powerful lobby groups in a democracy and the politicians are reluctant to deal with them on an issue so vital.
We still have to deal firmly with the inter generations problems which lie at the heart of the current economic dilemmas.
Our pension systems and our national budgets must be based on a "generational accounting" which ensures that economic risk is systematically divided between generations.
This means that pension and tax bodies shall be designed to take greater account of changing circumstances to face the different generations rather than frozen, promises that certainly cannot be held in any event, a certain recovery in the future.
For example, when demographic trends or endless economic events impose burdens on workers at the level of social benefits, the benefits owed to retirees must automatically be changed by the increase in the retirement age and / or adjustment of profits.
