Tax and spend (please).
Excessive taxation can dull incentives and hinder growth.
But inadequate taxation can also produce the same effects.
Governments with a meagre tax revenue cannot provide essential public goods.
Worse still, a low tax revenue in poor countries often arises from flaws systems (rather than low tax rates) tax collection which also encourage non-productivity.
The India illustrates the importance of a well-designed tax system.
Bangalore, high-tech companies have built world-class campuses full of manicured lawns and ultra - fast data communication networks.
Out of these campuses, however, lie open sewers, not collected garbage and roads in a State of advanced dilapidation.
While technology companies instantaneously transmit terabytes of data to distant continents, local transportation advances to an almost medieval look.
As a result, companies in Bangalore operate their own bus services, sous - deal with private providers to have drinking water, and install generators to protect against power failures.
The State cannot compensate for this disaster because it is in bankruptcy.
The India government debt exceeds 70% of GDP so that more than half of its tax revenues are devoted to repayment of interests.
But debt is not due to excessive spending in the past.
The India government expenditures represent approximately 15% of GDP, compared to an average of about 40% of the GNP of the OECD.
The financial difficulties of the India were rather due to an ill-conceived and mismanaged tax system.
Rates and rules for taxes on income of individuals and companies seem to be reasonable in the light of international standards.
However, the India Government imposes taxes on the income only about 3.7% of GDP, or about half of those in the Korea of the South and the other Asian Tigers.
Agriculture in India accounts for about a quarter of GDP, but even rich farmers pay no taxes.
Exporting companies in the software industry and other industries enjoy a tax holiday on profits, although their employees pay taxes on their personal income.
Despite reasonable rates, tax evasion is rife.
Fraud is explained by the fact that the Government has not invested in staff or systems to discover refractory taxpayers, who rarely go to jail and can often get out of business by paying bribes - - when ' they get caught.
More subtly, the loophole of "direct" taxes on incomes and profits reflects the clutter inherent in the system of the "indirect" taxes levied on production and consumption.
Excise duty account for more than 60% of indirect taxes of India, which in turn represent the same proportion of its total tax revenue.
Basic excise duty was set at 16% of the value of production of a company.
Then follow various reductions, exemptions and surtaxes.
For example, a "duty at concessional rate" of 8% is levied on categories like food, matches, cotton yarn and computers.
A "special excise duty" additional 8% is levied on products that include filaments in polyester, cars, air conditioners and tires.
"Additional excise duty" (not to be confused with the "right to special excise") is levied on "products of special importance".
Exemptions from excise duty are numerous and complex, including companies with total annual revenues of less than 10 million rupees and firms located in some troubled areas or backward.
Generally, the exemptions are divided into 70 categories, they - same sub - divided into 259 entries, 52 conditions and 7 lists, each containing many elements.
Exemptions lead to abuse.
For a certain amount, officials at the bottom of the hierarchy, which show an exemplary discretion in the application of the conditions, can be encouraged to provide favorable interpretations.
Products taxed at high rates (for example, polished granite) are sold as goods taxed at lower rates (for example, as of the granite unpolished).
Fraud concerning excise duty is more contagious than evasion on profits and revenues.
If a business fraud excise duty and tax rate is high compared with margins before taxes in the industry, competitors must also defraud simply in order to survive.
While fraud increases, Governments take "additional" or "special" rights that encourage greater fraud.
Perceptions of direct taxes also suffer.
The pot - de - vin paid to the collector of excise for a favorable classification, the difference between the value of polished and unpolished granite, and the failure to record true revenues create "black" funds that cannot be declared on income tax forms.
In addition to weakening the capacity of the State to provide essential public goods, systems for the escape from indirect taxes also discourage companies to adopt more productive technologies, which requires technologies involving a large-scale deployment.
But because indirect taxes may be more easily bypassed by deploying several small units instead of one large unit, it is impossible to achieve economies of scale.
It is important to note that in the software industry, where all units are exempt from indirect taxes, Indian companies operate on an effective scale.
The India could - it imitate the example of China, the country in which the rationalization of indirect taxes in 1994 paved the way for a big boom?
Or the coalition in a vigorous democracy Governments are - they incapable of such a reform?
Last year, the India BJP-led Government has enacted legislation allowing dramatic reductions in the budget deficit.
He then appointed a working group to make the changes necessary to bring public spending policies and tax policies.
Last July, the Working Group suggested raising taxes (rather than cut spending) by removing the majority of exemptions from taxes indirect, among other things.
The new Government led by the Congress of the India also seems to favour these proposals.
If the Congress and the opposition parties follow, they help much to support the economic growth of the country and to dispel the idea that democracies cannot take the necessary measures to encourage development.
