These conclusions, although contrary to popular perceptions of Saudi culture, are less surprising than they seem.
Sociologists of religion argue for a long time that in a monolithic religious environment, or when religious institutions are closely linked to the State, the overall religiosity of the population declines.
It makes sense to think that when the State authorities apply rigid behavioral codes, individuals tend to rebel and away from officially endorsed religious institutions.
It is thus hardly surprising that the Egyptians and Jordanians, who live in countries in which the State does not enforce piety, are more religious than Iranians or Saudis, who must deal with local 'virtue' supported by the State police.
Even on the issue of marriage, many Saudis expressed surprisingly liberal views.
Respondents were split almost evenly on the issue of arranged marriages, half supporting the idea that marriage should be based on parental consent, compared to 48% who considered love as the basis of marriage.
