Pigs, calves, and American democracy.
Among the flood of titles on the return of the Democrat majority in Congress after the November elections, the result of an important election has gone largely unnoticed.
Although it has highlighted the shortcomings of the American political system, it has also allowed me to believe again in the compassion of ordinary American citizens.
In Arizona, citizens can, if they have brought together a sufficient number of signatures, submit a draft law to the direct popular vote.
This year, one of the questions submitted by popular suffrage was a law to prohibit that pregnant sows, or calves reared for meat, are strapped or confined in a way that prevents them from turning freely, lie down or stretch their limbs.
Those who do not know the methods of intensive livestock amaze may be the need for such legislation.
Traditional livestock farming, as it is practiced everywhere in the world fifty years ago, and in some countries today, allows the animals to move and stretch.
But today, nearly 90 per cent of the sows - mothers of the pigs raised and slaughtered for meat, bacon and ham - spend most of their life in stalls which measure approximately 60 centimeters by 2, 2 m.
They cannot turn, extend their once-folded legs, nor forward or backward over a step.
They are also sometimes strapped to restrict their movements.
In the same way the calves are confined their lifetime in individual stalls where they cannot turn around, lie down or stretch.
Basically, these methods are designed to save labor costs. They facilitate the management of animals and allow to employ fewer workers and less skilled.
They also prevent animals wasting energy in to deplacdant or fighting among themselves.
A few years ago, following protests from animal rights organizations, the Commission of the European Union requested a report to the Standing Veterinary Committee of the EU on intensive farming methods.
The conclusions of the report indicate that the animals suffer from not being able to move and boredom of having nothing to whole days.
Of course, the simple common sense to arrive at the same conclusions.
In response to the report, the EU has set the dates from which the containment of farmed animals will be prohibited.
For calves, January 1, 2007.
Individual for sows, already prohibited stalls in the Kingdom - Uni and in Sweden, will be banned from 2013 throughout the European Union.
Measures to improve the welfare of hens, hens kept in battery cages truss without enough room to extend their wings, are also applied gradually.
States - United, nothing of the kind is expected.
Previously, when my European friends asked me why States - United accused such a delay in the well-being of livestock from Europe, I knew that answer.
If they insisted, I well say that one possible explanation was that Americans cared less animals than Europeans.
Then, in 2002, associations for the defence of animals managed to submit to popular vote a proposal to ban individual stalls for sows in Florida.
To General surprise, the proposal was accepted by 55 percent of voters.
Last month in Arizona, despite opposition generously funded by the agri-food industry, the ban on the boxes of containment for calves and pigs was also approved, by 62 percent of voters.
Neither Florida nor Arizona only are particularly progressive States â both voted for George W. Bush against John Kerry in 2004.
The results of these two popular votes so strongly suggest that if all Americans should take a decision on the maintenance of pregnant sows and calves in containment, a large majority oppose.
Ultimately, it seems that Americans are concerned about as much as Europeans to the living conditions of farmed animals.
To explain the difference between the welfare of livestock in Europe and the States - United, it is undoubtedly necessary to compare political systems.
In Europe, the concerns of voters about the living conditions of animals have found an echo among members of national parliaments and the European Parliament, with result the adoption of national legislation and EU directives to improve their lot.
States - United on the other hand, these same concerns had no visible effect on members of Congress.
There is no federal legislation on the welfare of farmed animals and virtually no legislation at the State level.
AB my opinion, tens of millions of dollars of the agri-food industry pocketed by officials seeking to be re-elected there is for something.
The movement for the defence of animals, despite strong popular support, does not weight in the arena of political lobbying and election donations.
In American electoral races, money is more important than the opinion of voters.
Party discipline is weak and delegates must collect themselves the bulk of funds for their re-election - in this case, every two years for members of the House of representatives.
In Europe, where party discipline is respected and where parties, and not the candidates, finance election campaigns, money plays a less important role.
States - United, a country proud of its democratic tradition, calves and pigs are by far not the only losers.
