A practical guide on the Israeli hawks.
The announcement of Prime Minister Ariel Sharon indicating willingness to dismantle the Jewish settlements of the Gaza Strip and some West Bank settlements has shocked and caught off guard the Israeli nation and the nations of the world.
Many denounced Sharon's plan as being a trick.
But this surprise was crazy from the beginning.
Despite the appearance that they give to foreigners, the debate in Israel about the future of the occupied territories were never reduced to a simple story of hawks and doves.
Like any thing in Israel, the process is more complex, and particularly where the hawks are concerned.
Overall, there are two species of Israeli Hawks: the ideological and the strategic.
Ideological hawks consider the occupied territories as part of the historical land of Israel, the homeland of the Jewish people.
For them, the territories are of Jewish heritage, which explains their insistence on calling the West Bank by its Hebrew historical appellation: Judea and Samaria.
Ideological hawks are not all religious, although those who are based their claim on promises and the divine prophecies.
But many ideological hawks are secular nationalists and their jargon is similar to that of the nationalists types of Eastern and Central Europe.
Former Prime Minister Menachem Begin and Yitzhak Shamir belonged to this category.
Ideological hawks usually belong to the National religious party and Likud.
They are inspired by a nationalist ideology associated with Vladimir Jabotinsky, who founded "revisionist" Zionism in order to challenge the more moderate version adopted by the founding fathers of Israel, including Chaim Weizmann and David Ben - Gurion.
Next strategic hawks.
For them, given the geographic form close and vulnerable Israel and the continuing hostility of Arabs, control of the West Bank and Gaza is not an ideological imperative, but responds to security considerations.
For them, the Jewish settlements in the territories do not constitute a return to historical lands, but represent bastions of security designed to prevent (or repel from a more strategic location) an attack in the heart of Israel.
This assessment of the situation may be right or wrong, but it is certainly not ideological.
Ariel Sharon, who comes from a medium military (he grew up in a social milieu whose ideas were more akin to the labour party than to Jabotinsky), is a strategic Hawk.
For ideological hawks, compromises are treason: how to put at risk the heritage of the Jewish people, not to mention the promise of God to Abraham?
Strategic hawks are however open to negotiations and practical compromise, if the circumstances and security considerations justify it in their eyes.
It is in this context that must be considered the measures taken by Sharon.
He was elected on the promise that he would bring peace and security.
He brought neither the one nor the other.
With the defeat and the demise of Saddam Hussein, the danger of an "Eastern front" against Israel has weakened.
Without a Palestinian partner, and due to continued Palestinian terrorism that the desperate actions of Israel fail to suppress, the measures taken by Sharon arise from this reflection oriented strategy: erect an effective barrier, move some of the colonies isolated and strategically untenable, and wait.
Sharon statements during the previous year seem to follow a well-defined pattern.
First, he admitted that"one day or the other", a Palestinian State would make his appearance, an inconceivable idea for pure ideological hawks.
A few months later, he scandalized his followers the Conference of party Likud by declaring that the occupation was unacceptable and untenable, another shock for those who had always talked about "liberated" rather than "occupied" territories.
Last December, he explicitly stated that Israel was facing a stop - the - unilateral fire that would inevitably result in the "relocation" of some settlements.
Although that these statements not akin once again that to a simple verbiage, they did in no less constitute a new language for a Likud Prime Minister.
The latest statements by Sharon yet explicitly appointed the settlements to be evacuated; the Director of the national Security Council, general Giora Eiland, was appointed president of an interdepartmental Committee of relocation to elaborate plans to evacuate settlements and provide compensation for relocated settlers.
All this has radically altered the domestic political map of Israel.
Some ideological hawks in Sharon's Government have threatened to resign; Shimon Peres announced that the Labour Party would offer Sharon a parliamentary safety net; There is also talk that the labour party to join a national unity Government.
The test is well obviously not planning, but the implementation of the withdrawal, and the road is long and bumpy.
The timing by Sharon may have been guided by the problems it encounters following police investigations into his alleged corruption.
However, anyone would predict the future behaviour of Sharon must keep in mind that in contrast to Begin and Shamir, Sharon has a military past and that for him, security, and not ideology, is paramount.
Thus, his apparent pragmatism should not surprise.
