Fight against drugs: we need to change policy.
Once more, the Russia and the Ukraine are victims of an illusion.
Since the end of communism in 1991, the use of drugs has increased dramatically in both countries (as well as many others).
They reacted by draconian measures in line with the simplistic policy aimed at the total elimination of drugs adopted by the United Nations.
These measures contribute today to the explosion of AIDS in a number of developing countries.
The UN conventions that govern the policy of combating drugs at the international level do not take account of recent discoveries on the drug use and dependence.
Most of these conventions have been established long before the advent of AIDS, which is spread mainly by intravenous drug use in the countries of the former Soviet Union and in many Asian countries.
Thus, at the international level, it is in Russia and Ukraine that AIDS is spreading more quickly.
The number of people infected there was multiplied by 18 over the past five years.
It is estimated that one and a half million Russians and 400,000 Ukrainians are affected and at least 85% of them are intravenous drug users.
In an attempt to wrongheaded to adhere to the UN conventions, the Russian and Ukrainian governments use the bulk of their means of combating drugs.
Drug users are victims of ill-treatment on the part of the police and are resisted by health services, even for vital care.
And meanwhile, drugs continue to flood the market.
On drugs, the repression has never managed to eliminate demand.
Repression takes into account economic and social factors nor public health considerations related to the use of banned substances.
Locking up drug users is not a solution; in Russia it is still easier to buy drugs in prison than outside.
In a repressive climate, drug users who escape arrest tend to be the subject of discrimination, which do not encourage them to protect their health or that of the people they are encountering.
If the company offers no hope for addicts and showed no compassion towards them, drug addiction and HIV AIDS cannot that grow quickly.
The Russia and the Ukraine are not only cope with the increase in intravenous drug abuse and the spread of AIDS which accompanies it.
If they continue this kind of policy, Pakistan, the Iran, China, Central Asian countries and all the countries that are in the same situation will be confronted with the same catastrophe in terms of public health.
Many studies around the world show that in the fight against drugs, the action in the field of public health is the most effective for reducing HIV infection and reduce the costs.
The British medical journal Lancet estimated that the USA would have saved at least $ 500 million if they had implemented a needle exchange programme at the national level during the period 1987-1995.
A survey conducted at the international level shows that HIV infection decreased by 5.8% in the cities where there is a needle-exchange program, but it increased by 5.9% in the cities where there's not.
No importance study highlights a correlation between the existence of a needle exchange program and an increase in drug abuse.
Business studies in the USA, Australia and elsewhere show that the number of drug addicts who receive treatment does not decrease, if because participants in needle exchange programs have easier access.
The UN agencies such as the Commission on drugs or the United Nations Office on drugs and crime (UNODC, ex - UNDCP) do not have mandate to prescribe a specific strategy to combat drugs.
However, their narrow conception of the fight against the drug exerts a strong influence on the policies and measures taken by Member States.
Many Governments, obsessed with compliance with the UN conventions, cannot or do not want to take into account the negative effects in terms of public health of a strictly repressive policy of fight against drugs.
In the 1990s, when AIDS began to kill millions of people in Africa, infecting more than a quarter of the population of some countries, international institutions have hijacked head.
For similar reasons, this terrible epidemic is about to hit among other countries of the former Soviet Union.
Have - we learned anything?
It is not too late, policy makers at the national and international level can still reconsider their strategy.
Despite the UN conventions, some countries have adopted a more pragmatic attitude towards drugs and AIDS.
Consider that it is first and foremost a problem of public health to more effectively combat the AIDS epidemic.
The following measures would achieve:.
Â· Adopt legislation anti - discrimination to ensure civil liberties and of the human rights of users of drugs and people affected by HIV.
Â· Recognize that the use of drugs is a problem of public health and non-compliance with law or law enforcement and to implement a policy that reflects this fact.
Â· Explicitly legalize the programs of exchange of syringes and methadone treatments and other substitute products.
Â· Establish programs national risk reduction that are pragmatic and accessible to all. This requires education, alternative therapies, detoxification programs and needle exchanges.
Â· Both at the national and international level, involve drug users and their advocates in the development of policy concerning drugs.
Refuse to reconsider the goals of combating anti - drug and selected strategies will only worsen the AIDS epidemic and contribute to the death of millions of vulnerable people.
The abandonment of the Lisbon resolutions.
Upon taking office at the post of President of the European Commission, Durao Barroso - former Prime Minister of the Portugal - should concentrate urgently to restore order and to refocus the economic policies of the European Union.
The thickest folder that awaits him is that of Lisbon resolutions, an ambitious programme approved in 2000 by the heads of State and Government of the European Union with the aim of making the Union 'the most competitive and dynamic economy' as early as 2010.
The main economic fields are covered: innovation and entrepreneurship, the reform of social systems and social inclusion, skills and employment, equality of the sexes at work, the liberalization of employment and property markets, as well as sustainable development.
It is certain that these are worthy ambitions but that inherently belong to the sphere of national political decisions.
Indeed, according to the European treaties, the Union has no competence to implement a legislative and political arsenal in these areas, nor the power to enforce.
However, the Council of Europe, encouraged by the European Commission, has invented a new political approach - called 'open coordination' - to be able to affect these areas.
Open coordination involves the determination of common objectives at EU level, a voluntary compliance on the part of the Member States and internal control of the results within the Council of Europe.
Obviously, open coordination has failed to keep its promises.
In addition, the illusion that the Council of Europe could somehow sommer growth and productivity has provided a diversion to national politicians who do not want to promote at the national level of unpopular decisions.
Thus, I would suggest to Mr Barroso, as a first step, to get rid of the Lisbon resolutions.
It is the only thing to do to make it clear that national responsibilities remain in the hands of national politicians in terms of economic performance.
This brings me to the macroeconomic coordination at the level of the European Union.
The Maastricht Treaty envisaged a political framework for economic and monetary union.
Monetary policy was centralized and entrusted to an independent Central Bank, while fiscal policy remains the responsibility of the Member States.
National Governments were subject to the dual constraint - under the control of excessive deficits procedure - to prevent fiscal deficits of more than 3% of GDP and budget deficits more 60% of GDP (or at least around this value).
Subsequently, the stability and Growth Pact added an additional criterion, in the medium term, to ensure that national budgets are "balanced or almost".
This was, essentially, to prevent irresponsible budgetary policies after the launch of the euro, while leaving enough space for cyclical oscillations of the deficits within the limit of 3%.
The credibility of this arsenal of measures was greatly undermined by the public controversy of November 2003 between the Commission and the Ecofin Council on the application of the procedure of control of excessive budget deficits to the France and the Germany.
Which does not mean that it should be abandoned.
On the contrary, a common external constraint on fiscal behavior is necessary to serve as guard - crazy together against an accumulation of unsustainable public debt, which could affect financial stability and inflation throughout the European Union - a risk increased by the impact of aging populations on pension systems.
Such a constraint also provides an anchor for the national decision-making in Member States whose political systems are less reinforced.
But the system must be reviewed.
I will not listen those who defend the exclusion of investments fiscal deficits: this would only further encouragement for creative accounting and unsustainable accumulation of debt.
Instead, it should focus on the sustainability of the debt rather than on the annual deficits.
The debt criterion, for example, could be accompanied by a limitation on (trends of) the growth of the rate of public expenditure, which would be kept below the rate of nominal GDP.
The power of the Commission to launch the movement when there is risk of excessive deficits should be strengthened - until, of course, the Commission more never forgets that the monitoring of national policies is a task that requires a certain political meaning and cannot be left in the hands of managers and lawyers.
Finally, he should make European integration the main priority that the Union has at its disposal a powerful legal instrument to force open markets and strengthen competition.
The best therapy to revive growth must be both directly, through the increase in competitive pressure, indirect, by the outbreak of the measures necessary for the adaptation of national policies on employment, social protection and education.
This is a long-term task.
State subsidies for the benefit of companies in loss of speed remain ambiguous and the common laws designed to ensure the free movement of goods and services are not fully respected by the Member States - procurement and energy are the best examples.
In addition, most services markets - securities trade, the distribution of wholesale and retail, business services and local public services - remain sheltered from competition and regulatory free - exchange.
There is evidence that show that these distortions of the market for services that represents two-thirds of GDP are responsible for the bulk of the deficit of productivity that undergoes the EU vis - Ã  - vis States - United.
In recent years, the Council of Europe gave insufficient attention to these tasks, which involve a commitment to total and constant on the part of Member States to transpose and implement directives European.
All too often, the Commission has promoted the implementation of new legislation and the creation of new spending programs instead of the effective management of what is already in place.
Thus, Mr Barroso should forget the platitudes of top-flight Lisbon resolutions and focus instead on the effective implementation of the single market and put order in the fiscal policies of the Member States.
Let local governments assume responsibility for their country's economic performance.
