Political earthquake in Israel.
The Israeli political world is experiencing changes in the most impressive he has known for 30 years.
The realignment of parties and leaders is especially notable given the unexpected nature of the latest events in date: decision of Ariel Sharon to leave the Likud, the defeat of Shimon Peres as leader of the Labour Party and the withdrawal of the Labour Party of the grand coalition Government of Sharon.
It is more important than to grasp the meaning of these changes for the future of Israel, the region and the Israeli - Arab.
Schematically, the Israeli political system nears the end of its second era.
From independence in 1948 until 1977, the labour party has dominated, before yielding the place to an opposition coalition composed of conservatives, nationalists and centrist parties allied in the Likud bloc.
Since that time, the two parties successive ruling in turn, sometimes under broad coalitions and partnership with smaller parties sometimes.
On the surface, the rivalry between parties is played between "left" and "right", or "Hawks" and "Doves".
The truth, of course, is more complex.
Social class and economic problems, in the shadow of more persistent existential concerns, such as physical security and sustainability of the State have played a much less important role in Israel than in other societies.
Here, the political divide could be defined as the clash of the "optimistic" and "pessimistic".
The first, the Labour Party, believed that one day a force would prevail among Arabs and Palestinians ready to make peace on reasonable bases, while the latter, the Likud, were more circumspect.
For years, the discussion remained an abstraction, a debate about what might happen in the future, until the Oslo with the PLO in 1993 only begin to test rival visions.
Since 2000, the date where the leader of the PLO Yasser Arafat has rejected a political agreement and began instead a terrorist war in five years, there are few optimists.
The intellectual realignment that resulted in Israel gave birth to a new national consensus.
It is now widely accepted that, as the left has always said, Israel must be ready to withdraw from the West Bank and the Gaza Strip and to accept the existence of a Palestinian State in Exchange for real peace.
But it is also widely accepted that, as the right has always supported him, none of the partners is really ready to make peace.
Within this context, Sharon won two overwhelming election victories as a radical while applying a moderate policy, including a total withdrawal from the Gaza Strip.
This is where is Israel today, facing a political upheaval fueled by two new elements.
First, Sharon moved the Likud to the Center, and indeed any hegemonic party by destroying all stereotypes about his personality, his methods, and his vision of the world.
It is however, for the same reason that many members of the Likud view Sharon, who helped found the party, as a traitor.
Sharon now needs to institutionalize his reforms, even if it is necessary to establish another party for this.
Secondly, the labour party has demonstrated its political bankruptcy, because its only conceivable leader was a Shimon Peres aged 82 years and its anachronistic optimism from Dove was turned into ridicule.
As a result, and thanks to a low rate of participation in the elections, the party primaries were won by Amir Peretz, outsider and populist who wants to revive the Labor Party, highlighting the social and economic problems, which means the withdrawal of the coalition of national unity with Likud.
Although it must form a new party, Sharon will probably win the next elections it has scheduled for February.
Peretz strategy will attract may be voters other left-wing parties, but labor will surely lose centrist voters (and those for whom national security is a priority) for the benefit of Sharon.
