If the IDE can bring many benefits, there are also sometimes costs.
In the 1970s, when transnational corporations (TNCs) throwing in such investments began to get noticed, many Governments believed that the costs of FDI outweighed their profits and therefore controlled it.
The pendulum, held by developed countries, began fidgeting in the 1980s.
Once viewed as part of the problem, the IDE became a part of the solution to economic growth and development.
Nothing illustrates it better than changes in national FDI regimes.
As reported by the the United Nations Conference on trade and development, among the 2,156 changes that took place between 1991 and 2004, 93% were aimed at creating a more hospitable environment for TNCs.
But the risk of seeing the pendulum turn upside down is real, with result a decline in this liberalisation process.
FDI in developed countries (and increasingly in emerging markets) often takes the form of mergers and cross-border acquisitions.
Resistance to such approaches became more frequent when they involve firms that politicians consider 'national champions' or who play a role in national security, economic development or cultural identity.
The increasing involvement of capital companies - investment in the activities of mergers and acquisitions raises other controversies, because such transactions are typically considered to be purely speculative.
In the name of "economic patriotism", security and other considerations, resistance to mergers and acquisitions is codified in an increasing number of countries.
For example, a Committee of the U.S. Senate has recently tried to block the project of liberalization of foreign takeover rules for airlines, and Europe has implemented more restrictive takeover laws.
In addition, Governments apply more strictly existing regulatory provisions concerning the control of takeover bids by foreign companies.
This response is linked to a defensive reaction to the growing role of TNCs from emerging markets, "small news".
TNCs already well established, and their country of origin, will have to adapt to this new constellation of forces and its implications for the global market.
As other contexts have learned us, it is not easy to adapt to new entrants: compare, for example, the reaction between french Alcatel and American Lucent to offers by the China National Offshore Oil Corporation for Chevron or even that of Mittal for Acelor.
Another kind of defensive reaction, this time towards FDI outward, could well arise when the offshoring of services will have picked up speed.
Everything indicates that offshoring has reached a threshold and that this phenomenon will accelerate through the IDE.
If the countries of origin do not put in place of adjustment mechanisms to adapt to the fast revolution that makes marketable services sector jobs, a backlash against such FDI outward will be inevitable.
Increasing discomfort caused by the IDE is for the moment confined to developed countries.
Some signals yet that it extends to emerging markets.
