Emergency brake assistance is now mandatory.
As this took place with the anti-lock brake system ABS system and this will take place with the ESP stability control, emergency brake assistance systems will be a mandatory element on European cars.
They are already mandatory on passenger cars and light commercial vehicles newly registered, while for the rest of the vehicles a waiting period has been set until "late February 2011.
The measure, imposed by the European Union, has aimed to strengthen the protection of pedestrians, even if, because of its mode of action, it can also help prevent many rear shocks.
Emergency braking assistant works by increasing the pressure on the brakes in an emergency detected by the system through the kick given by the driver.
But does not always maintain pressure until "at the end.
According to a study conducted by the manufacturer of components for cars Bosch, a third of drivers involved in an accident was unable to press the brake before the collision, and half of them had not taken advantage of any strength.
Until "1 100 accidents.
The intervention of the assistance, en revancha, requires maximum brake system, reducing the distance whose car need to stop.
According a study by the EU, if all cars were equipped with this type of "elements, until" 1 100 fatal accidents in which pedestrians are involved could be avoided each year.
This reduction would be even greater with the popularization of the so-called intelligent emergency braking systems: we calculate that a disaster on four with injuries would be avoided.
In this case, the vehicle is equipped with a system which, thanks to a radar or a camera, detects obstacles and warns the driver, in addition to acting slightly on the brakes.
If the driver reacts, helps it by increasing the pressure on the pedal, if necessary.
If it does not react, and although the collision is inevitable, the device exerts maximum effort on the brakes to minimize damage.
